    {
      "id": "urn:article:1-s2-0-s0167404816301377-main",
      "type": "schema:ScholarlyArticle",
      "title": "A survey of cloud computing data integrity schemes: Design challenges, taxonomy andfuture trends",
      "authors": [
        "Faheem Zafar",
        "Abid Khan",
        "Saif Ur Rehman Malik",
        "Mansoor Ahmed",
        "Adeel Anjum",
        "Majid Iqbal Khan",
        "Nadeem Javed",
        "Masoom Alam",
        "Fuzel Jamil"
      ],
      "year": "2017",
      "doi": "10.1016/j.cose.2016.10.006",
      "journal": "computers & security",
      "abstract": "Cloud computing has gained tremendous popularity in recent years. By outsourcing computation and storage requirements to public providers and paying for the services used,customers can relish upon the advantages of this new paradigm. Cloud computing pro-vides with a compar ably lower -cost, scalable, a location-independent platform for managing\nclients' data. Compared to a traditional model of computing, which uses dedicated in-house infrastructure, cloud computing provides unprecedented benefits regarding cost andreliability. Cloud storage is a new cost-effective paradigm that aims at providing high avail-ability, reliability, massive scalability and data sharing. However, outsourcing data to a cloudservice provider introduces new challenges from the perspectives of data correctness andsecurity. Over the years, many data integrity schemes have been proposed for protectingoutsourced data. This paper aims to enhance the understanding of security issues associ-ated with cloud storage and highlights the importance of data integrity schemes for outsourceddata. In this paper, we have presented a taxonomy of existing data integrity schemes usefor cloud storage. A comparative analysis of existing schemes is also provided along witha detailed discussion on possible security attacks and their mitigations. Additionally, wehave discussed design challenges such as computational efficiency, storage efficiency, com-munication efficiency, and reduced I/O in these schemes. Furthermore, we have highlightedfuture trends and open issues, for future research in cloud storage security.",
      "keywords": [
        "Cloud computing security",
        "Storage as a service",
        "Data integrity",
        "Privacy preserving audit",
        "Communication complexity"
      ],
      "objective": [
        "This paper aims to enhance the understanding of security issues associ-ated with cloud storage and highlights the importance of data integrity schemes for outsourceddata."
      ],
      "problem": [
        "Fre-quent changes in cloud-based services also cause problems forusers. 4.Cloud storage provider stability Cloud storage claims to provide high availability.",
        "Besides the said tradeoffs, security of data integrityschemes becomes a challenging problem when dynamic dataoperations (insert, update, and delete) are supported."
      ],
      "methodology": [
        "Popular cloud-based storage ser-vices available today are Dropbox, One Drive, Amazon S3, GoogleDrive, Box, and Sugar Sync etc. Nowadays, to improve busi-ness strategies, organizations use analysis techniques over theirhistorical data ( Liu et al., 2014 ).",
        "Ap-plication of these techniques extended from a single copy tomultiple copies of data ( Krzywiecki and Kuty, 2012 ), constraintbased data geolocation (CBDG) ( Rashid et al., 2013 ), multicloud (cloud of clouds) ( Cash et al., 2013 ), data deduplication (Zheng and Xu, 2012 ) and proof of ownership ( Zhu et al., 2012 ).",
        "Researchers used homomorphic tags, bilinear pairing ( Wang and Zhang, 2014 ), algebraic signatures ( Yu et al., 2014 ), fountain codes ( Shi et al., 2013 ), erasure codes ( Chen, 2013 ), RS codes based on Cauchy matrices ( Chen and Curtmola, 2012b ) and other techniques as metadata for integrity verification."
      ],
      "contributions": [
        "The key contributions of this paper are: 1.",
        "Another sig-nificant contribution of this work is that it supports a largenumber of users without affecting the performance of theverification process ( Wang et al., 2012 ).Shen and Tzeng's (2011) scheme supports delegation of auditing authority; however, there is a restriction of re-delegation.",
        "Other major contributions of this work areindependent metadata size, reduce disk seeks, and support fordynamic data."
      ],
      "futureWork": [
        "Weestablish the timeline of the evolution of data integrity schemesand also identify future aspects that researchers can exploitto perform their future research."
      ],
