    {
      "id": "urn:article:1-s2-0-s0167404818301895-main",
      "type": "schema:ScholarlyArticle",
      "title": "SNAPS: Towards building snapshot based provenance system for virtual machines in the cloud environment",
      "authors": [
        "BKSP Kumar Raju",
        "G Geethakumari"
      ],
      "year": "2019",
      "doi": "10.1016/j.cose.2019.05.020",
      "journal": "computers & security",
      "abstract": "Recent threats in cloud show the necessity to perform forensics in the cloud environment. \nBut performing forensic investigation in the cloud is different from traditional digital forensics. Cloud characteristics like multi-tenancy, rapid elasticity, diversity, and complexity raise \nadditional challenges for cloud forensics. For each cloud Virtual Machine (VM), there will \nbe several evidences like vdisk, vRAM, Snapshots, Volumes, Service logs, and VM logs. The \nforensic challenges differ from one evidence to the other. In this paper, we look at the challenges of snapshot acquisition and analysis . In reality, snapshots for a VM may not always \nexist. To increase their availability, we suggest the use of Cloud Forensic Readiness (CFR) \nmodels in which the snapshots are collected before the actual incident. The captured snapshots have to be transferred to the investigators environment via network. Since the cloud \nVM snapshots will be generally of huge size, transferring them elsewhere for processing \nmay lead to the problem of data gravity. We resolve this problem by designing a framework \nnamed SNAPS (Snapshots based Provenance Aware System) which is derived from the existing spatio-temporal models and then customized to suit cloud forensic investigation. The \nmotivation behind proposing SNAPS is to generate provenance for each object in the target \nvirtual machine using its multiple snapshots. Moreover, SNAPS can be used to address various forensic challenges starting from simple to complex ones. Few of those were illustrated \nwith the VM snapshots acquired from the Openstack Cloud Environment.",
      "keywords": [
        "Cloud computing",
        "Digital forensics",
        "Snapshot acquisition",
        "Snapshot analysis",
        "Forensic readiness"
      ],
      "objective": [
        "In this paper, we look at the challenges of snapshot acquisition and analysis .",
        "In this paper, we intend to solve the challenges of investigation when the VM snapshots are used as the evidence."
      ],
      "problem": [
        "Since the cloud VM snapshots will be generally of huge size, transferring them elsewhere for processing may lead to the problem of data gravity.",
        "We resolve this problem by designing a framework named SNAPS (Snapshots based Provenance Aware System) which is derived from the existing spatio-temporal models and then customized to suit cloud forensic investigation.",
        "S. No. Challenges in Snapshot acquisition and analysis Sections in which we address these challenges 1 Snapshots act as one of the richest source of evidences during forensic investigation but they may not be available in all the cases."
      ],
      "methodology": [
        "The difficulties in the issue of data gravity would get worse when the evidences of huge size have to be acquired from the cloud and processed at the investigator's environment. • Anti-forensics: Techniques used as countermeasures for the forensic analysis.",
        "These techniques can complicate the entire forensic process. • Cloud service Provider (CSP): CSP owns and maintains the cloud resources and rent them to the users with less cost. • Intruder: A person who violates the underlying policies of the environment (here cloud) and performs suspicious activities or attacks. • Tenant: A tenant can have a single user or multiple users.",
        "Once any attack or suspicious activity is accomplished by the intruder then his usual task is to follow appropriate anti-forensic techniques through which the possibility of him being caught may be reduced and sometimes made impossible ( Harris, 2006 )."
      ],
