    {
      "id": "urn:article:1-s2-0-s0167404818303948-main",
      "type": "schema:ScholarlyArticle",
      "title": "A self-protecting agents based model for high-performance mobile-cloud computing",
      "authors": [
        "Pelin Angin",
        "Bharat Bhargava",
        "Rohit Ranchal"
      ],
      "year": "2018",
      "doi": "10.1016/j.cose.2018.04.011",
      "journal": "computers & security",
      "abstract": "Mobile-cloud computing (MCC) allows devices with resource and battery limitations to \nachieve computation-intensive tasks in real-time. While this new paradigm of computing \nseems beneficial for real-time mobile computing, existing MCC models mainly rely on keeping full clones of program code at remote sites and unstandardized/uninteroperable environments, hampering wider adoption. Moreover, the security risks arising from offloading \ndata and code to an untrusted platform and the computational overhead introduced by \ncomplex security mechanisms stand as deterrents for adoption of MCC at large. In this \npaper, we present a context-dependent computation-offloading model for MCC, which is \nbased on application segments packed into autonomous agents. This approach only requires isolated execution containers in the cloud to provide a runtime environment for \nthe agents, and minimal involvement of the mobile platform during the computation process. The agents in the proposed model are able to protect themselves from tampering \nusing integrity-checkpointing and an authenticated encryption-based communication \nmechanism. Experiments with two mobile applications demonstrate the effectiveness of \nthe approach for high-performance, secure MCC.",
      "keywords": [
        "Mobile-cloud computing",
        "Tamper resistance",
        "Autonomous agents",
        "Performance",
        "Security"
      ],
      "objective": [
        "In this paper, we present a context-dependent computation-offloading model for MCC, which is based on application segments packed into autonomous agents.",
        "In this paper we present a mobile-cloud computation model based on autonomous agent-based application modules, which are augmented with performance checkpoints for self-performance evaluation and integrity verification units for dynamic detection and reporting of code tampering."
      ],
      "problem": [
        "Recent work on this problem has resulted in frameworks with various partitioning and optimization techniques.",
        "The other major obstacle for wider adoption of MCC is the security risks associated with sending sensitive data and code 77 (2018) 380-396 381 to an untrusted platform, including but not limited to the following: • Lack of control on resources and multi-tenancy of different users' applications on the same physical machine make cloud platforms vulnerable to attacks ( Feng et al., 2011 ). • In addition to privacy issues, programs running in the cloud are prone to tampering with code, data, execution flow and communication, as well as masquerading attacks ( Chou, 2013 ). • Mobile code can navigate through multiple platforms before returning to the origin, giving rise to the end-to-end security problem, which involves decreasing control with every further hop in the chain of platforms ( Ali et al., 2015 )."
      ],
      "methodology": [
        "Recent work on this problem has resulted in frameworks with various partitioning and optimization techniques.",
        "However, most of these frameworks impose strict requirements on the cloud side, such as a full clone of the application code or special application management software, hindering wide applicability in public clouds.",
        "Achieving ultimate flexibility and performance in mobile-cloud computing is contingent upon the availability of a secure computing framework capable of dynamic decision making with regards to the execution location of different program partitions."
      ],
      "contributions": [
        "The main contributions of this paper are as follows: • We present an effective and easy-to-adopt dynamic computation offloading model for high-performance MCC. • We present a dynamic performance estimation model that allows for tracking and relocation of offloaded computation to ensure optimal performance under varying mobilecloud context. • We propose a tamper resistance model for MCC that allows for dynamic integrity-checking and migration of offloaded computation to ensure trustworthiness of results received from a cloud platform. • The proposed computation offloading and protection model relies on lightweight, transparent mechanisms for application code transformation/augmentation, allowing for low response time overhead and high interoperability."
      ],
