    {
      "id": "urn:article:1-s2-0-s0167404821000845-main",
      "type": "schema:ScholarlyArticle",
      "title": "Optimized extreme learning machine for detecting DDoS attacks in cloud computing",
      "authors": [
        "Gopal Singh Kushwah",
        "Virender Ranga"
      ],
      "year": "2021",
      "doi": "10.1016/j.cose.2021.102260",
      "journal": "computers & security",
      "abstract": "Distributed denial of service (DDoS) attack is a serious security threat to cloud computing \nthat affects the availability of cloud services. Therefore, defending against these attacks becomes imperative. In this paper, we present a DDoS attack detection system based on an improved Self-adaptive evolutionary extreme learning machine (SaE-ELM). SaE-ELM model is \nimproved by incorporating two more features. Firstly, it can adapt the best suitable crossover \noperator. Secondly, it can automatically determine the appropriate number of hidden layer \nneurons. These features improve the learning and classification capabilities of the model. \nThe proposed system is evaluated using four datasets namely, NSL-KDD, ISCX IDS 2012, \nUNSW-NB15, and CICIDS 2017. It achieves the detection accuracy of 86.80%, 98.90%, 89.17%, \nand 99.99% with NSL-KDD, ISCX IDS 2012, UNSW-NB15, and CICIDS 2017 datasets, respectively. The experiments show that the performance of the proposed attack detection system \nis better than the system based on original SaE-ELM and state-of-the-art techniques. However, it shows a longer training time than SaE-ELM based system.",
      "keywords": [
        "Cloud computing",
        "DDoS attack",
        "Artificial neural network",
        "Extreme learning machine",
        "Differential evolution"
      ],
      "objective": [
        "In this paper, we present a DDoS attack detection system based on an improved Self-adaptive evolutionary extreme learning machine (SaE-ELM)."
      ],
      "problem": [
        "To overcome these problems, optimization of input-hidden link weights and hidden biases for ELM are proposed in the literature."
      ],
      "methodology": [
        "Furthermore, the automatic determination of the appropriate number of hidden layer neurons is also incorporated using the technique proposed in Eshtay et al., 2020 , which eliminates the need for manual setting.",
        "Related work In Rathore and Park (2018) , the authors proposed a method based on the combination of extreme learning machine and semi-supervised fuzzy c-means algorithm.",
        "The ELM is trained using the training dataset and the membership degree of samples in the unlabeled dataset is computed using semisupervised c-means."
      ],
