    {
      "id": "urn:article:1-s2-0-s0167404822004114-main",
      "type": "schema:ScholarlyArticle",
      "title": "Security analysis and improvement of a public auditing scheme for secure data storage in fog-to-cloud computing",
      "authors": [
        "Wenfang Zhang",
        "Heng Jiao",
        "Zhuoqun Yan",
        "Xiaomin Wang",
        "Muhammad Khurram Khan"
      ],
      "year": "2023",
      "doi": "",
      "journal": "Computers & Security",
      "abstract": "Human society has drastically changed as a result of the widespread application of Internet of Things (IoT) \ntechnology, particularly in various industrial fields. In spite of the advantages brought by IoT services, \nthe underlying security challenges cannot be underestimated. Cloud-based IoT data collection poses a \nnumber of challenges, including how to ensure its integrity. In order to address this issue, Tian et al. \nhave proposed a fog-to-cloud computing-based public auditing scheme in IoT scenarios, which provides \nthe data-privacy preserving mechanism and tag transformation strategy. However, in this paper, we show \nthat Tian et al.'s scheme fails to achieve soundness, an essential security property, by giving two attacks. \nIn the first attack, the malicious cloud server can delete all the data and then deceive the Third Party \nAuditor (TPA) into believing that the data is well-preserved. In the second attack, the malicious cloud \nserver can modify the outsourced data and then deceive TPA into believing that all the data is kept intact. \nWe further provide a simple but effective solution for Tian et al.'s scheme to resist the above-mentioned \nattacks. Security analysis and performance evaluation are also given to demonstrate the robustness and \nhigh efficiency of the improved scheme.",
      "keywords": [
        "Cloud storage",
        "IoT",
        "Data integrity checking",
        "Fog computing",
        "Security analysis"
      ],
      "objective": [
        "In this paper, we investigate the details of Tian et al. (2019) and analyze its security."
      ],
      "problem": [
        "Moreover, to handle the problem of user revocation in dynamic group under cloud data sharing scenario, Wang et al. (2015) proposed a novel scheme, named Panda.",
        "To tackle the problem that authenticatable tag of metadata generated by different mobile sinks with different keys, they designed a novel tag transforming strategy, which converts tags produced by mobile sinks to the ones produced by fog nodes."
      ],
      "methodology": [
        "This method makes use of error correction and random permutation so that data owner can detect the changes of stored files.",
        "In Sun et al. (2020) ; Tian et al. (2019) ; Wang et al. (2014) ; Zhao et al. (2019) , authors also took different methods to achieve user information privacy preserving, like random mask encryption, ring signature and so on.",
        "Experimental results In this subsection, we evaluate the performance of our improved scheme and give a performance comparison with the other two schemes involved in Table 2 ."
      ],
      "contributions": [],
      "futureWork": [],
